## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

Your code matches the **timeout enforcement** pattern. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`).

### What's wrong in .NET 8

| API | Problem |
|-----|---------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`), no-ops |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if work() itself doesn't check the token.
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Prefer this async version when callers support async
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw; // caller cancelled — propagate, don't wrap
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls

1. **Cooperative cancellation can't force-stop uncooperative code.** Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, cancellation only works at checkpoints. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop that never checks the token, `Task.WaitAsync` will return with a timeout but **the work keeps running on the thread pool**. To truly stop it, the `Func<T>` must accept and check a `CancellationToken`:

    ```csharp
    // Better: pass the token into the work
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        // ... same pattern
    }
    ```

2. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it holds timer resources. Always `using`.

3. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — only catch it at the orchestration point (as shown). Use the `when` guard to distinguish timeout from external cancellation.

4. **Uncooperative third-party code** — if you truly need force-kill semantics (like the old `Thread.Abort`), move work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. There is no in-process equivalent in modern .NET.

5. **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** — it's the key API that makes the sync version clean. It throws when the token fires regardless of whether the inner task cooperates.
